ustice systems in the United States and Canada. Justice for Girls? is a comprehensive comparative study of the way these countries have responded to the hysteria over “girl crime” and how it has affected the treatment of both girls and boys. Tackling a century of historical evidence and crime statistics, Jane B. Sprott and Anthony N. Doob carefully trace the evolution of approaches to the treatment of young offenders. Seeking to keep youths out of adult courts, both countries have built their systems around rehabilitation. But, as Sprott and Doob reveal, the myth of the “girl crime wave” led to a punitive system where young people are dragged into court for minor offenses and girls are punished far more severely than boys. Thorough, timely, and persuasive, Justice for Girls? will be vital to anyone working with troubled youths.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFemale juvenile delinquentszCanada. 0aFemale juvenile delinquentszUnited States. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzCanada. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ayouth, juvenile courts, criminal justice, law, legal system, united states, canada, women, gender, femininity, criminology, female criminality, girl crime, punishment, prosecution, paternalism, reform, deinstitutionalization, adolescence, nonfiction, bad girls, delinquency, administrative offense, status offender reforms, social norms, fear.1 aDoob, Anthony N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aZimring, Franklin E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprint